\exp(iz^2)
X
T \to \infty
X
z= (1+i)w
\int_{\Delta} \exp(iz^2) dz = 0
\lim_{T \to \infty} \left \vert \int_{T}^{T+iT} \exp(iz^2) dz \right \vert \leq  \lim_{T \to \infty} \int_{T}^{T+iT} \left \vert \exp(iz^2) \right \vert \vert dz \vert = \lim_{T \to \infty} \int_0^T \exp(-2Tx) dx\\ = \lim_{T \to \infty} \dfrac{1-\exp(-2T^2)}{2T} = 0
\int_{0}^T \exp(iz^2) dz = \int_{0}^{T+iT} \exp(iz^2) dz
\int_{0}^{T+iT} \exp(iz^2) dz = \int_0^T \exp(i(1+i)^2 w^2) (1+i) dw = (1+i) \int_0^T \exp(-2w^2) dw
\lim_{T \to \infty}\int_{0}^{T} \exp(iz^2) dz = (1+i) \dfrac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2\sqrt{2}}
\int_0^{\infty} \sin(x^2) dx = \text{Imag} \left( \int_0^{\infty} e^{ix^2} dx\right)=\dfrac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2\sqrt{2}}
